paragraphs.text:
%md
# Our Machine Learning Problem Statement
We would like to teach the computer to understand the difference between Kid Safe content, Safe For Most Audiences and Safe for Adults. This is a simple ML problem but we will see in the first naive pass over the data that we will need to enhance the dataset in order to train our Model to `choose correctly` when given a decision to make.

## Steps to get to our first Model

1. We will learn of to use Feature Engineering techniques to Reduce the complexity of our Data. This includes Indexing, Encoding, Scaling and Bucketing/Binning our Data.
2. We will figure out a simple way to Encode categorical labels for our Ratings (TV-MA, R, NC-17,...) and our Categories (Kids and TV, Horror, ...)
3. We will then look a `Pipelines` in Apache Spark. These are similar to scikit-learn Pipelines and help to create a Phase-Based series of Transformations over a DataFrame.
4. We will then finish up looking at how to model a naive K-Means model (unsupervised) and view the relationship between Categories and Ratings.

  1. We will learn of to use Feature Engineering techniques to Reduce the complexity of our Data. This includes Indexing, Encoding, Scaling and Bucketing/Binning our Data.
  2. We will figure out a simple way to Encode categorical labels for our Ratings (TV-MA, R, NC-17,…) and our Categories (Kids and TV, Horror, …)
  3. We will then look a Pipelines in Apache Spark. These are similar to scikit-learn Pipelines and help to create a Phase-Based series of Transformations over a DataFrame.
  4. We will then finish up looking at how to model a naive K-Means model (unsupervised) and view the relationship between Categories and Ratings.

## Encoding the Category and Ratings Rows and Back Again
1. Using StringIndexer to encode of Categories and Ratings to double values
2. Using the IndexToString transformer we can get back to our original String Values!

msg.data:
Encoding the Category and Ratings Rows and Back Again

  1. Using StringIndexer to encode of Categories and Ratings to double values
  2. Using the IndexToString transformer we can get back to our original String Values!

paragraphs.text:
%spark
import org.apache.spark.ml.feature.{IndexToString, StringIndexer}
val categoryIndexer = new StringIndexer()
  .setHandleInvalid("keep") // options are keep, skip, error
  .setInputCol("category")
  .setOutputCol("category_index")

val ratingIndexer = new StringIndexer()
  .setHandleInvalid("keep")
  .setInputCol("rating")
  .setOutputCol("rating_index")

val invalidHandler = ratingIndexer.handleInvalid

// now we can index the categories by using a distinct on the dataset (contentWithCategories) since we fit to an arbitrary dataset

val fittedCategoryIndexer = categoryIndexer.fit(contentWithCategories.select("category").distinct())
val fittedRatingIndexer = ratingIndexer.fit(contentWithCategories.select("rating").distinct())

// now we can call transform on our fitted indexers

val contentWithIndexedCategories = fittedCategoryIndexer.transform(contentWithCategories)
val contentWithIndexedRatingsAndCategories = fittedRatingIndexer.transform(contentWithIndexedCategories)

contentWithIndexedRatingsAndCategories.show(10, false)

val categoryIndexConverter = new IndexToString()
  .setInputCol("category_index")
  .setOutputCol("category")

val ratingIndexConverter = new IndexToString()
  .setInputCol("rating_index")
  .setOutputCol("rating")

val converted = categoryIndexConverter.transform(contentWithIndexedRatingsAndCategories
  .drop("category")
  .drop("rating")
)


val originalDataRestored = ratingIndexConverter.transform(converted)

originalDataRestored.select("category","category_index").distinct.sort(asc("category")).show(100, false)
originalDataRestored.select("rating", "rating_index").distinct.sort(asc("rating")).show(100, false)
originalDataRestored.show(10, false)

originalDataRestored.printSchema

paragraphs.text:
%md
## What is K-Means Clustering?

In a nutshell, simple K-Means clustering attempts to partition a dataset across a predefined set of (K) centroids or points in 1-dimensional space in an iterative fashion.

A mental exercise would be to think about a basket of fruit with 4 types of fruit (apples, banannas, peaches and pears). You can only define the size or color of the fruit and now you must partition a truck load of fruit into logical groups with only these two types of data.

Let us look at the Size of fruit use case
[ apples : 1 ]
[bananas : 3 ]
[ peaches : 1 ]
[ pears : 2 ]
1. We select an arbitrary K value of 2 (in theory apples, peaches and pears are smaller than banaas)
2. The algorithm will first randomly select 2 points within the numeric space of the size of fruits (say from 1 - 4) and it selects 2 and 4.
3. As the algorithm iterates over the data it will attempt to place or cluster the data into groups based on the distance from their value to the value of the centroid. 
4. This algorithm typically uses [`Euclidean Distance`](http://rosalind.info/glossary/euclidean-distance/) to find the distance from a data point to the cluster centers.

paragraphs.text:
%md
## What is One Hot Encoding?
One Hot Encoding is a process that takes our Indexed values and `encodes` these values into a vector of [0,1]. In the case of our Fruit example from before.

### Before One Hot Encoding using the index values

|name|index|
|---|---|
|apple|0|
|banana|1|
|peach|2|
|pear|3|

### After One Hot Encoding
|name|index|encoding|
|---|---|---|
|apple|0|1, 0, 0, 0|
|banana|1|0, 1, 0, 0|
|peach|2|0, 0, 1, 0|
|pear|3|0, 0, 0, 1|

## Why should you care?
Remembering that Computers love numbers and are not very intuitive on their own, they end up `thinking` that you care about `rank` for your indexed labels. Given that rank matters when a computer is sorting / scoring and modeling continous data (say `connected_seconds` for recommending new movies to a user), but shouldn't be apply a rank of 0-50k or higher (Netflix auto incrementing id values). This would mean that new movies win which applied a stupid bias.

%md
## Introducing SparkML Transformation Pipelines
Machine Learning is about all repeatable results. Given that there are numerous steps to transform our data from the initial csv file in part one until now it seems like there is a better way to accomplish these data pipelines. The answer is `yes`.
1. Apache Spark ML introduced the Pipeline primative to enable you to reliably apply multiple transformations (mutations) to your data in a phasic approach.
2. We will see a simple example below of how to use the Pipeline and we will go into more details in section 3.

1. Apache Spark ML introduced the Pipeline primative to enable you to reliably apply multiple transformations (mutations) to your data in a phasic approach.
2. We will see a simple example below of how to use the Pipeline and we will go into more details in section 3.

paragraphs.text:
%spark
import org.apache.spark.ml.Pipeline
import org.apache.spark.ml.feature.OneHotEncoderEstimator
import org.apache.spark.ml.feature.VectorAssembler
import org.apache.spark.ml.clustering.KMeans
import org.apache.spark.ml.evaluation.ClusteringEvaluator


val encoder = new OneHotEncoderEstimator()
  .setInputCols(Array("category_index","rating_index"))
  .setOutputCols(Array("category_vec", "rating_vec"))

val vectorAssembler = new VectorAssembler()
  .setInputCols(Array("category_vec","rating_vec"))
  .setOutputCol("features")

/*val vectorAssembler = new VectorAssembler()
  .setInputCols(Array("category_index","rating_index"))
  .setOutputCol("features")*/
  
val transformationPipeline = new Pipeline()
    .setStages(
        Array(
            encoder,
            vectorAssembler
        )
    )

val fittedPipeline = transformationPipeline.fit(contentWithIndexedRatingsAndCategories)

val transformed = fittedPipeline.transform(contentWithIndexedRatingsAndCategories)

val kmeans = new KMeans().setK(4).setSeed(1L)

val model = kmeans.fit(transformed)
val predictions = model.transform(transformed)


val evaluator = new ClusteringEvaluator()
val silhouette = evaluator.evaluate(predictions)

println(s"Silhouette with squared euclidean distance = $silhouette")

// Shows the result.
/*println("Cluster Centers: ")
model.clusterCenters.foreach(println)*/

predictions.createOrReplaceTempView("predictions")

Given that PG movies and NC-17 show up in the same cluster

  1. Set a Double value for Movies and Shows that are for kids, sensitive groups or anyone (0.0, 1.0, 2.0)
  2. Apply this transformation to enhance the clustering

paragraphs.text:
%spark
/*
+---------+------------+
|rating   |rating_index|
+---------+------------+
|G        |6.0         |
|TV-G     |11.0        |
|TV-Y     |9.0         |
|TV-Y7    |8.0         |
|TV-Y7-FV |1.0         |

|TV-PG    |0.0         |
|PG       |4.0         |
|PG-13    |2.0         |
|TV-14    |12.0        |

|NR       |10.0        |
|R        |13.0        |
|NC-17    |7.0         |
|TV-MA    |3.0         |
|UR       |5.0         |
|__unknown|14.0        |
+---------+------------+
*/
val SafeForKids = Seq(1.0, 6.0,8.0,9.0,11.0)
val SafeForMost = Seq(0.0,4.0,2.0,12.0)

def withRatingClassification(df: DataFrame): DataFrame = {
  df.withColumn("rating_class", when(col("rating_index").isInCollection(SafeForKids), 0.0D).when(col("rating_index").isInCollection(SafeForMost), 1.0D).otherwise(2.0D))
}

val contentWithRatingClassification = contentWithIndexedRatingsAndCategories.transform(withRatingClassification)
contentWithRatingClassification.printSchema
contentWithRatingClassification.createOrReplaceTempView("rating_classification")

%spark
import org.apache.spark.ml.Pipeline
import org.apache.spark.ml.feature.OneHotEncoderEstimator
import org.apache.spark.ml.feature.VectorAssembler
import org.apache.spark.ml.clustering.KMeans
import org.apache.spark.ml.evaluation.ClusteringEvaluator


val encodeRatings = new OneHotEncoderEstimator()
  .setInputCols(Array("category_index","rating_index","rating_class"))
  .setOutputCols(Array("category_vec","rating_vec","rating_class_vec"))

val vectorAssemblerRatings = new VectorAssembler()
  .setInputCols(Array("category_vec","rating_vec","rating_class_vec"))
  .setOutputCol("features")

val transformationPipelineRatings = new Pipeline()
    .setStages(
        Array(
            encodeRatings,
            vectorAssemblerRatings
        )
    )

val fittedPipelineRatings = transformationPipelineRatings.fit(contentWithRatingClassification)
val transformedRatings = fittedPipelineRatings.transform(contentWithRatingClassification)

val kmeans = new KMeans().setK(4).setSeed(1L)

val modelN = kmeans.fit(transformedRatings)
val predictionsN = modelN.transform(transformedRatings)
predictionsN.createOrReplaceTempView("predictions_new")

%md
## What we learned
1. Unsupervised Learning Methods can help you group (or partition) your data logically and help you see emerging patterns
2. With some additional Domain knownledge you can help assist the models to automatically group data into sub-clusters (in our case we added the 3 grouping parameters to see how the additional feature `rating_class` could help)
3. Using `StringIndexer` and then `OneHotEncoderEstimator` on our indices (category_index, rating_index) along with our rating_class performs better clustering. This is because when we index our categorical features like we did with the category and rating strings, the `StringIndexe`r creates values that look like 0.0, 1.0, etc. Our machine learning algorithms can mistake these values as Ranking values eg. 1.0 is less than 50.0 so we don't want the ordinal style value to be mistaken so we encode with OneHotEncoder*

## Next Steps (http://localhost:8080/#/notebook/2F3D4HQRX)
We will be learning how to do binary classification on our dataset using LogisticRegression
1. LogisticRegression is a great classification algorithm for predicting a binary label (eg. hotdog / not a hotdog)
2. In our case we are going to modify the Netflix Movies data using what we've learned to predict if a movie is safe for kids
3. The idea is to train the model using the rating_class, rating_index, category_index as well as some indexed keywords from the Movie descriptions
4. Let's get going!
